			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			11/26 3:12pm 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> RE: Bored of EQ,UO,DAOC what would you want from a game ?			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I posted this a long time ago. <br>  <br> I will describe the game as if it has already been created and an experienced player (Joe) is helping his friend (Bob) create his first character.  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, the first thing you are gonna do is choose what race you want to play. You have 100 points to spend, but you are going to need points later so use them all up on your race selection.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK what do I have to choose from?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, you got all the traditional fantasy races to choose from and much more.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Really? I can play an orc?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Sure, an orc, a goblin, a giant&#8230; even a dragon.  <br>  <br> (Bob) I can play a dragon?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, not now you can&#8217;t. You only have 100 points and a dragon cost&#8230; (Scrolls down the list) 10,000 points.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Ten thousand? Geeze, how do I ever get that many?  <br>  <br> (Joe) You&#8217;ll earn them by playing the game. You can use them for special things, or save them for your next character.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Wow, that&#8217;s cool, but it must be a wimpy dragon huh?  <br>  <br> (Joe) No, I wouldn&#8217;t call it wimpy. You start off as a young dragon and have to go on from there. You have the potential to become a great wyrm of ancient age, but you&#8217;d have to be pretty crafty to reach that point.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK, that&#8217;s something to look forward to. I like elves though, I guess I will start off as an elf.  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, yeah, elves are cool, they have some special abilities that humans don&#8217;t have.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Yeah, I want to be an elven mage named Crowsyr, who blasts his foes with bolts of lighting bzzzzz!  <br>  <br> (Joe) Hee hee, well put your wand away for now Crowsyr, with 100 points you wont be blasting anybody yet.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Whadda you mean?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Elves are a rare race my friend, that&#8217;s why they cost so much. Look, an elf cost 75 pts. A human only cost 50. The goblin only 25. You get bonuses with the elf that you don&#8217;t get with a human such as infravision and long life. You can play an elf now, but with only 25 points left, you will have little to spend on magic casting abilities and your stats.  <br>  <br> (Bob) I was kinda lookin&#8217; forward to playing an elven mage though.  <br>  <br> (Joe) And you will, you just have to earn that ability. This point system was put in place as a way to balance the game. Otherwise, everyone would figure what would be the best race and class and then everyone would play that class. With this system, it forces us to be balanced. Through the life of the game, you will have people in all of the stages of character development. The races that cost the least will be the most populated, while the races that cost the most, will have the smallest population. Obviously the Dragon is the most powerful of the races, and therefore the most costly and available to only a few players at a time.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK I see. I guess it&#8217;s better to learn the ropes first. I would still like to play a mage though. How about a human&#8230; or can an orc play a mage?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Go for the human. The orc can do magic, but you&#8217;d spend so much getting his intelligence and dexterity up to do it, it wouldn&#8217;t be worth it.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK human mage it is.  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK  <br>  <br> (Joe selects &#8216;human&#8217; on the race selection screen and then clicks &#8216;next&#8217;)  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, now for stats. Human&#8217;s start off with pretty average stats. We&#8217;ll boost your intelligence up some, and give you a higher agility. There, now you have 35 points left. Lets buy your skills.  <br>  <br> (Joe helps Bob select some skills. He needs Wizadry which takes a good chunk of his remaining points, and Joe helps him choose some other skills that will give him a decent chance starting out.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) I noticed that wizadry was expensive and those combat skills are too. It would cost a lot to make a character who was good in both areas.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yes, that&#8217;s true. Wizardy is supposed to be an art practiced by scholarly men. The developers of the game don&#8217;t want it filled with spell casting tanks. Warriors have their place as well as Wizards. It is possible to have the ability to do both, but only to players who are determined and work for it. If you see a spell casting warrior, you will know, that that player payed a high price for that character.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK I have 6 points what next?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Starting equipment.  <br>  <br> (Bob) You mean I gotta buy that too?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Of course, and this is where the thrifty player gets his due, the more points you have, the better the stuff you can buy. Remember the goblin that cost 25 pts? If you would have bought him, you could enter the game with some pretty kickin&#8217; equipment for a goblin. Most gobs never amount to anything, but PC gobs are different. They are an above average kind of goblin. So they get some better stuff. It gives them a fighting chance considering the weaker stats they start out with. It&#8217;s all in the balance.  <br>  <br> (Bob) I get it. I see I can get a basic mage package for 4 points. That leaves me with 2. What can I get with that?  <br>  <br> (Joe) You can convert it to gold or save it for your next character.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Oh, that&#8217;s cool. Hey, what if I had a whole lot left over? Couldn&#8217;t I just make a bunch of first level characters and add up all the points?  <br>  <br> (Joe) No, it don&#8217;t work that way Bob. There&#8217;s checks and balances. The developers know how crafty players are. There&#8217;s limits put in the game to preven players from abusing the system.  <br>  <br> (Bob) But what if I earn the points the right way?  <br>  <br> (Joe) You still can&#8217;t create a character from scratch and give him an overpowering advantage over other players. The point system gives the developers the ability to fine tune and tweak the races and abilities, so that its fair and fits within the scope of the game. If they find that too may Giants are roaming the world, then simply raise the cost of the giant race.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK, well what&#8217;s next?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Choose your face and you&#8217;re ready to set foot in the world  <br>  <br> End Part I  <br>  <br> (Joe has finished helping Bob set up his account and created his character. Bob chose the name Migas for his human mage and now they have netered the game world in a small villiage known as Bathel)  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, first thing's first, take a look at your inventory and see what you have.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK I bought that basic mage kit. It came with a wooden staff, a robe, a pouch, a back pack, a water skin, and some trail rations.  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK put the robe on, equip the staff and lets go fill your water skin.  <br>  <br> (Bob) You mean I have to eat and drink?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yes, but dont worry about it, food doesnt cost so much that you wont be able to feed yourself.  <br>  <br> (Bob) How do I eat?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well there's two ways. You can eat those rations there by clicking on them, or you can go over to that inn and order a meal.  <br>  <br> (Bob) What's the difference?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Eating can be a social thing. Eating trail rations is fine to keep you alive in the wild, but if you go to that inn and go through the process of having a meal, you will earn some character points.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Really? That easy?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yes, but its only a few points and you can only do it once per real time day. The point is to get people to go to inns and interact.  <br>  <br> (Bob) I see, that's cool.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yeah, this game isnt just about killing or getting loot. There's alot of stuff like that, that you can find that will give you points. Now, there is a well, click on it and you will fill your waterskin.  <br>  <br> (Joe finishes helping Bob learn the basics of moving about and getting things done. Now Bob is itching to do soemthing.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK Can I kill something now?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, what do you want to kill? You're in the middle of a villiage. There's someone standing over there, you wanna go kill him?  <br>  <br> (Bob) Well who is he? How do I know I can kill him?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Click on him  <br>  <br> (Bob clicks on the man and his text display gives him a response.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) It says, &quot;an unknown human.&quot;  <br>  <br> (Joe) Hail him by pressing the 'h' key.  <br>  <br> (Migas) Hail friend, I am Migas.  <br>  <br> (Leary) Greetings Migas, my name is Leary. Perhaps you can help me with a quest?  <br>  <br> (Bob) This is kinda like that other game.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Kinda, but not exactly. Go on accept the quest.  <br>  <br> (Migas) What is the quest?  <br>  <br> (Leary) I need some herbs found in the Whailing Wood. I am willing to pay 6 GP for each bag you bring to me. I would go myself, but I have another pressing matter.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Come on! This is just like that other game.  <br>  <br> (Joe) No actually, it's a bit more. For one, this NPC, may not even have been here giving this quest yesterday. Or maybe, he wont be here tomorrow. You see, many of the quests are dynamically generated. Some of them are based on the economy, some based on politics at the moment. The quests constantly change. Many are more involved than this one. Some even counteract each other, so for you to complete your quest, somone else will not be able to complete his.  <br>  <br> (Bob) That's cool. How do I know I can do this quest? Maybe that place is too rough.  <br>  <br> (Joe) No, he wouldn't have offered the quest if you were, so you dont waste your time. Still it could be dangerous.  <br>  <br> (Migas) I will do your quest.  <br>  <br> (Leary) Wonderful, the herbs are known as Willow Roots and can be found in the Whailing Wood.  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK before you go, click on him again.  <br>  <br> (Bob clicks on the man and his text screen displays a message.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) Now it states his name but before it stated only &quot;an uknown human.&quot;  <br>  <br> (Joe) That's because you know him now. It works the same for player characters too. Do one more thing. Ask him what he thinks of the king.  <br>  <br> (Migas) What do you think of the king?  <br>  <br> (Leary) The king is a good ruler the people love him. Long live King Hermann!  <br>  <br> (Bob) What was that for?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Just to see what the current feeling about the king is. It seems he's doing well, but that all may change so keep up with it.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Who is this hermann guy anyway?  <br>  <br> (Joe) He's a player just like you.  <br>  <br> (Bob) He got to be the king?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yes, he somehow managed to attain that goal. You can too.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Well that guy must play a lot. I wont be able to keep up with him, I have a wife and kids.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Perhaps, but you maybe able to attain another position of power. That could be one of your goals for the game, ot maybe you just want to go kill stuff. It's up to you.  <br>  <br> (Bob) But it sounds like it can be abused. You know, a big guild gets together and they all work together to get one of them to be the king and then share all the loot between themselves. I hate that kind of stuff.  <br>  <br> (Joe) No, being king isnt that easy. There are many decisions that you need to make and you need to keep your people happy. If Leary here hated the king, then there'd be some trouble brewing. He may have given you a quest that leads to King Leary's downfall.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Oh wow, this is sounding cooler as I learn it.  <br>  <br> (Joe) It gets better. Let's go get them herbs.  <br>  <br> End Part II  <br>  <br> (Joe shows Bob around town and then eventually to the wilderness area outside of town.)  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, I know this area well. The Whailing Wood is just to the south of town.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK, this is a PVP game right? What if someone PK's me?  <br>  <br> (Joe) You mean like a grief player, who does it just for the fun of ruining someone's day?  <br>  <br> (Bob) Yeah  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, you always have to be on the lookout, but in this game, grief players have a hard time making a living.  <br>  <br> (Bob) How so?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, for the same reasons that people just dont go around killing each other in real life. The concequences are too great. Most games that have a problem with grief players is because players can get away with murder literally. In this game, when you die, your character is dead. A person will think twice about going into combat because it may be the end of him if he does. If a player invests time in a character then that means he usually wants to hang on to him. Player killing is a risky business.  <br>  <br> (Bob) But what about the guys who just make new characters and hang around newbie areas attacking people for no reason?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Under certain conditions, the game will subtract points from your total if you commit a killing blow. What this means is unless this guy has a large store of points to waste, he is going to end up having les than 100 points to build a character. This would make it even harder for him to PK.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Killing blow?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Yes, a killing blow was put in to prevent accidental death. A player must commit a 'killing blow' to finish off an opponent, otherwise, you are just knocked unconscience. NPC's will sometimes leave you for dead too. Death in this game doesnt come as easy as other games. You have a chance to run away, but even if you dont, it doesnt mean certain death.  <br>  <br> (Bob) OK, that's cool. Hey look there's someone up ahead on the road.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Be careful, though grief players are rare in this game, thieves and robbers are not uncommon. Use that spell I had you buy 'Reveal Hidden'  <br>  <br> (Migas casts a spell)  <br>  <br> (Joe) There! See them hidden in the bushes? It was an ambush. He would probably stop you and ask you something, then his friends would jump you. You should avoid them, take this other path.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Wow, that was scary. Its a good thing I have you with me. Tell me more about combat.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Well, most games are based on hit points. The higher you go, the more you have. In this game, your hitpoints are set, based on your race and other factors like your constitution and some skills. As your character grows in skill, these hit points increase only marginally, but your ability to avoid damage increases dramatically. So the difference between a new character and a well seasoned character is the new character gets hit more for more damage, while the seasoned character gets hit less for less damage.  <br>  <br> (Bob) What about armor?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Armor has the same affect for a new character as well as a well seasoned character. For example. If a monster hits a newbie for 10 points of damage, that same blow may do only 3 to a well seasoned warrior. If they where both wearing the same kind of armor, then that same blow would do even less.  <br>  <br> (Bob) What about weapons.  <br>  <br> (Joe) Doing damage is really much the same. The more experienced you are, the more often you will hit and the more damage you will inflict. Look, there's a giant spider. Want to try your art?  <br>  <br> (Bob) Yes!  <br>  <br> (Joe) OK, go for it.  <br>  <br> (Joe helps Bob vanquish the spider and after that they collect the roots for the quest. Upon returning to town, they turn in the roots, and Bob gets some gold coins, some experience, faction, and 10 character points. Over all it was well worth the effort.)  <br>  <br> (Bob) So can I do the quest again?  <br>  <br> (Joe) This one you can, but you'll get less experience and less character points.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Bummer  <br>  <br> (Joe) There are other quests, or maybe you can try a trade.  <br>  <br> (Bob) What kind of trade?  <br>  <br> (Joe) Anything really. Almost all items in the game are player made.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Really? Why?  <br>  <br> (Joe) It's part of the living economy. It serves several purposes. For one, camping is eliminited. Nobody sits and waits for Monster X to spawn so that they can get Item X. Also, the prices of items are based on supply and demand. That means, money has real value. Another thing that it affects is politics. For instance, the best iron in the game is mined in the Red Mountains. The dwarves that live there guard it like it was gold. They mine it, turn it into Red Mountain Steel and sell it to merchants who then sell it to armor and weaponsmiths. A couple of months ago, the dwarven miners joined forces and now they control who gets to mine the ore and when it can be mined. This hasn't sat too well with some of the other 'free' miners and now a bloody war is going on over it. It has also affected the prices of quatlity weapons throughout the land.  <br>  <br> (Bob) Wow. What about magic items?  <br>  <br> (Joe) A skilled craftsman can create a quality item. The more skill he has, the better it's quality. Magic items on the other hand are even more powerdul and rare. They are more powerful because they are imbued with spells, and they are more rare because the caster has to use character points to create the item. The more powerful the item, the more character points that go into it. If you get your hands on a magic item, you will cherish it. It's not like other games where magical items just literally appear out of nowhere and are usually worthless. Players only will create an item if they have a use for it. OK, lets move on.  <br>  <br> End Part III <br>  <br>  <br> 
