			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			11/27 3:26pm 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> RE: Bored of EQ,UO,DAOC what would you want from a game ?			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				Sounds like Horizons, because I borrowed a little from Horizons, a little from EQ, a little from AC, DAoC, and even the Vaporware Dawn. <br>  <br> I think a successful game would have to cater to all 4 of Bartle's personality types. <br>  <br> Achievers <br> Explorers <br> Socializers <br> and  <br> Killers. <br>  <br> It sounds impossible, but it IS entirely possible. DAoC is a good idea, but it caters mainly to the PK'er. EQ's strengths are for achievers and Socializers, AC with it's vast open spaces and no zones perhaps appeals to the Explorer the best, but no game satisfies all 4 types. <br>  <br> The problem is, the people themsleves conflict with each other. Killers and Socializers don't mix very well for example. Today's MMORPG's attempt to fix that by artificial barriers. EQ &amp; AC put the PK'ers on their own servers, DAoC separates PK'ers with artificial level barriers. It's fine, but those barriers limit roleplaying. A great MMORPG should find away so that both Killers, and Socializers can coexist on the same server, but in such a way that one group doesn't have an advantage over the other. In the real world, we have Killers &amp; Socializers too. The killers do not have free reign to slay everyone they see, but they do kill and get away with it. <br>  <br> In my world, the socializer may never need to leave the safety of his city. He can become a politician, hold meetings, and whatever. He should never have to lift a sord in order to become successful. <br>  <br> The Killer could live his life differently. He can prey on the bold adventurers that dare enter his domain, or if he is bold himself, he can go looking for trouble, but more than likely his life will be short lived. <br>  <br> The Achiever has much to look forward to in a game like this. Saving enough points to become a dragon, and then a successful one should be a huge achievement. <br>  <br> The Explorer would also have a lot to look forward to. The world would be ever changing, not because the game maker changes it, but because the players would be.  <br>  <br> I think a great MMORPG is possible without the artificial barriers of level limits and no-drop items etc. It just has to be designed that way. We have had many games to learn from. The first big step though is getting away from the &quot;main&quot; character syndrome. That's where a player starts a game, and has a main character that he levels from 1st to whatever the highest level is. In order for this to be possible, the game maker has to put in a whole bunch of artificial rules in like death being temporary and PK switches etc. Real life is not like that. Think about it, one of the biggest thrills in life is risking your life. Playing one of todays MMORPG's is sorta like bungee jumping off of a step ladder. Death should be permanent, but also, the player should be rewarded for long play, so if you lose your 150th level character, you don't exactly start over from scratch. <br>  <br> I don't think Horizons satisfies all of these ideas. I don't like the fact that anybody can just go and be a dragon any time they want. I don't know though, I haven't looked into it that much. It may be a great game if it is ever made.
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
