			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			11/28 9:04pm 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> RE: Bored of EQ,UO,DAOC what would you want from a game ?			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				[TheRook - I like the fear aspect of these games, the greater the penalty for dieing the greater the fear, &#8220;in my game when you&#8217;re dead YOUR DEAD that&#8217;s it !!&#8221; I thought.  <br> But then I got to thinking supposing a player has been playing carefully for months even years, perhaps a master tradesman with lots of friends, and one day he&#8217;s trained by some idiot or goes link dead , and dies through no fault of his own.  <br> Would that player pack the game in ?  <br> I think I would , for a while anyways. :/] <br>  <br> That's the whole idea behind having points. When you die, the player should have amassed some points to start a new character. Maybe now, he has more points though, so he has a better choice of races and classes to choose from. In addition, it shouldn't take forever to level in this kind of game. When it taks 6 months to make high level, the point of the game becomes the leveling. If you make leveling easier, then leveling for the sake of leveling loses it's charm. The emphasis should be on living and making the best of it. <br>  <br> Another idea I was tossing about is how aquiring new spells and skills. Melee types can learn new fighting techinques in the same way casters find new spells. When killing a mob, a player may find a peice of the puzzle to gain the new spell/skill. The clue will always lead the player to where he has to go next. The trick is, it's never in the same place twice. So if you find a clue to researching the spell Fire Ball, and it tells you the 2nd piece is in the Temple of Doom, that may not hold true for your next character who may have to go to the Library of Maloch to find the second piece. What this does is sends people on personal quests. It's kinda like the research in EQ, except, it's not a haphazard chance of killing the monster and hoping he has page 126 etc. Also, there will be no cheater websites that spell out all the things you have to do to complete quest X. <br>  <br> If you guys like these ideas, then spread them about. Who knows, maybe someone will &quot;steal&quot; them and the game will get made.
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
